            "creation_date": 1449945391,
            "body": "<p>This is a classic coin change problem which is NP. But there are dynamic programming approaches for solving it for limited size of the problems. For more information:<br>\n<a href=\"http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/dynamic-programming-set-7-coin-change/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/dynamic-programming-set-7-coin-change/<\/a><br>\n<a href=\"http://www.algorithmist.com/index.php/Coin_Change\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.algorithmist.com/index.php/Coin_Change<\/a><br>\n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Change-making_problem\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Change-making_problem<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 34243485,
            "question_id": 34243379,
            "last_edit_date": 1449945990
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "user_type": "does_not_exist",
                "display_name": "user5650917"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1449944956,
            "creation_date": 1449944956,
            "body": "<p>I'm not going to write the code for you but this should give you a good idea.<\/p>\n\n<p>Check if the largest (15L) is less than the reservoir. If it is, reduce the reservoir by that amount and make a note that 1 x 15L has been selected. Repeat this using smaller and smaller buckets until you have nothing left (or a remainder).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 34243421,
            "question_id": 34243379
        }
